
# PyTorch unit test audit

## How to use 
## part 1. PyTorch unit test trend
## If you already have the xml test-reports, jump to Step 3
1. Export Github account token
   ```
   export GITHUB_TOKEN=YOUR_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN
   ```
2. Install the requirements: pip3 install -U -r requirements.txt
3. Download latest testlogs and xml for both ROCm and CUDA (NOTE use the --arch flag for whichever architecture you are interested in. It will default to mi355)
   `./download_testlogs 2>&1 |tee download_testlogs.log`
   Note the download folder name AND that the user needs --ignore_status if there were failures on the workflows that are being downloaded
   (Optional) Download latest testlogs only for ROCm
   `./download_testlogs --no_cuda 2>&1 |tee download_testlogs.log`
   (Optional) Download latest testlogs excluding distributed
   `./download_testlogs --exclude_distributed 2>&1 |tee download_testlogs.log`
   (Optional) Download testlogs for a specific commit sha and without checking status
   `./download_testlogs --sha1 <commit_sha> --ignore_status 2>&1 |tee download_testlogs.log`
   (Optional) Download testlogs for a specific pr excluding distributed, inductor, and without checking status
   `./download_testlogs --pr_id <pr_id> --exclude_distributed --exclude_inductor --ignore_status 2>&1 |tee download_testlogs.log`
4. Summarize the test logs using xml workflow
   `python summarize_xml_testreports.py --set1 <set1_xml_dir> --set2 <set2_xml_dir> --skip_reasons ut_test_skip_reasons.csv --output_csv <output file name>`
   Notes: --set1 and --set2 can point to any downloaded xml directory. Each download creates a folder containing
          rocm_xml_dir and cuda_xml_dir subdirectories. You can mix and match any of these freely:
          - ROCm vs CUDA (same run): --set1 <DIR>/rocm_xml_dir --set2 <DIR>/cuda_xml_dir
          - ROCm vs ROCm (cross-arch, e.g. MI300 vs MI355): --set1 <MI300_DIR>/rocm_xml_dir --set2 <MI355_DIR>/rocm_xml_dir
          - CUDA vs CUDA (compare across runs): --set1 <DIR_A>/cuda_xml_dir --set2 <DIR_B>/cuda_xml_dir
          - Same dir against itself (sanity check): --set1 <DIR>/rocm_xml_dir --set2 <DIR>/rocm_xml_dir
          - Single set (no comparison): provide only --set1 to summarize a single set of test-reports
          User can also use --filter option to specify unit test status for each set, with the format of <status_of_set1>-<status_of_set2>.
          Sample command to filter test cases that are skipped and missed on ROCm but NOT on CUDA:
          `python summarize_xml_testreports.py --set1 rocm_dir --set2 cuda_dir --filter SKIPPED-NOT_SKIPPED-MISSED-NOT_MISSED --skip_reasons ut_test_skip_reasons.csv --output_csv <output file name>`
   (Optional) Use --set1_name and --set2_name to customize the column header names in the generated CSV.
          By default, columns are named status_set1, status_set2, etc. With custom names, they become status_<name>, e.g.:
          `python summarize_xml_testreports.py --set1 rocm_xml_dir --set2 cuda_xml_dir --set1_name rocm --set2_name cuda --output_csv <output file name>`
          This produces columns like status_rocm, status_cuda, message_rocm, message_cuda, running_time_rocm, running_time_cuda.
5. Opening the generated CSV in Excel
   Open Excel and use File > Open or Data > From Text/CSV (Get Data > From File > From Text/CSV) to import the CSV.
   This ensures proper column separation and avoids issues with commas in test messages.
6. Checking for catastrophic failures
   If test results look suspicious (e.g. large numbers of MISSED tests), the CI run may have hit a catastrophic failure
   that prevented XML reports from being generated. Search the downloaded log files for these patterns identified by the
   PyTorch team as common indicators of catastrophic failures:
   - `SIGIOT` — abnormal process termination (often an assertion failure in a native library)
   - `Command took >30min` — a test shard timed out and was killed before completing
